    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Natural gas is a reliable, low‑carbon fuel that can be quickly scaled to meet peak demand, but it still emits CO₂ during combustion and requires significant infrastructure and water for extraction. Wind energy, by contrast, produces no direct emissions during operation and can be deployed with minimal land‑use disruption, yet it is intermittent and demands substantial upfront investment and maintenance. In comparison, natural gas offers a more consistent power supply and lower levelized cost of energy (LCOE) in the short term, while wind energy provides a cleaner, long‑term solution that can be expanded to meet growing renewable capacity. Ultimately, the best approach is to use natural gas as a bridge to wind, ensuring a stable grid while accelerating the transition to cleaner energy.",
